{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534750"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15179"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.16,0.01,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7870"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"2248"},{"type":"tags","id":"2254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is referred by nursing staff to the covering junior doctor overnight with increasing oxygen requirements. She was admitted two days ago following an elective total knee replacement. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications other than postoperative analgesia. She has been mobilising with physiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on 4 L/min oxygen via nasal prongs, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her chest is clear on auscultation. The operative site shows minimal strikethrough on the dressing, with some associated redness, discomfort, and swelling in the leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn arterial blood gas reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.48 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 58 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 30 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 22 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her hypoxaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opioid toxicity","Hospital-acquired pneumonia","Atelectasis","Aspiration pneumonia","Pulmonary embolism"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute hypoxaemia following recent surgery, with blood gas findings showing type 1 respiratory failure (hypoxaemia with hypocapnia) and respiratory alkalosis. Understanding the alveolar-arterial (A-a) gradient is crucial for determining the cause of hypoxaemia. The A-a gradient is calculated using the formula: A-a gradient = PAO2 - PaO2, where PAO2 = (FiO2 \u00d7 [Patm - PH2O]) - (PaCO2/0.8). For this patient on 4L nasal prongs (approximately 36% oxygen): PAO2 = (0.36 \u00d7 [760 - 47]) - (30/0.8) = 257 - 37.5 = 219.5 mmHg. Therefore, A-a gradient = 219.5 - 58 = 161.5 mmHg (normal \u003C15 mmHg).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe A-a gradient is a powerful tool for differentiating causes of hypoxaemia. In hypoventilation, the A-a gradient remains normal because oxygen transfer across the alveolar-capillary membrane is intact - the problem is simply inadequate ventilation delivering oxygen to the alveoli. In contrast, conditions causing V/Q mismatch (like pulmonary embolism), shunt, or diffusion impairment result in an increased A-a gradient because oxygen cannot effectively transfer from alveoli to blood despite adequate ventilation. This patient\u0027s markedly elevated A-a gradient immediately rules out pure hypoventilation as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the combination of recent orthopaedic surgery (a major risk factor), sudden onset hypoxaemia with tachycardia and tachypnoea, type 1 respiratory failure pattern, and significantly elevated A-a gradient indicating V/Q mismatch. The hypocapnia reflects compensatory hyperventilation in response to hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E causes hypoventilation, leading to type 2 respiratory failure with hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis. Crucially, the A-a gradient would remain normal in pure opioid-induced hypoventilation. This patient shows the opposite pattern - hypocapnia with an elevated A-a gradient - definitively excluding opioid toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHospital-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops after at least 48 hours of hospitalisation and would present with fever, productive cough, and abnormal chest examination findings such as crackles or consolidation. The clear chest on auscultation and absence of fever make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause an elevated A-a gradient through V/Q mismatch, but typically improves with mobilisation and physiotherapy. The sudden deterioration after initial mobilisation and the degree of hypoxaemia make this less likely than pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with witnessed aspiration event, cough, fever, and abnormal chest findings particularly in dependent lung zones. The clear chest examination and lack of risk factors for aspiration (such as altered consciousness or swallowing difficulties) make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type 1 respiratory failure (low PaO2, normal/low PaCO2) with an increased A-a gradient suggests a ventilation-perfusion mismatch or diffusion impairment.","The alveolar-arterial oxygen gradient helps differentiate hypoventilation (normal A-a gradient) from V/Q mismatch, shunt, or diffusion impairment (increased A-a gradient).","Acute pulmonary embolism commonly presents with sudden onset hypoxia and respiratory distress following surgery."],"references":["Mirabile VS, Shebl E, Sankari A, et al. Respiratory Failure in Adults. [Updated 2023 Jun 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526127/","Bhutta BS, Alghoula F, Berim I. Hypoxia. [Updated 2024 Mar 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482316/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T20:27:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T20:34:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7870"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"http